#X text 57 32 Here are two patches where the cuttof of the filter is set by a decaying envelope. Below to the left we have a [glide~] object working as a ASR envelope with a short attack/release of 10ms., f 38;
#X obj 245 309 adsr~ 0 500 0 10;
#X text 57 126 The [adsr~] envelope below has a decay stage that controls the filter and a short release to match the [glide~] release., f 38;
#X obj 566 311 pow~ 4;
#X obj 566 245 adsr~ -lin -minsus 0 0 1000 0 0, f 20;
#X text 618 181 Here a single envelope controls the amplitude and the filter., f 31;
#X text 632 296 The envelope is linear so it controls a proper filter frequency sweep in seminotes. For the amplitude \, we make it pass through a quartic function., f 37;
#X text 641 368 The envelope is set to a minimum sustain time of '0'. This means it always finishes the decay stage \, even if the gate was released before it finished., f 34;
#X obj 440 375 moog~ 0 0.75 0.5;
#X text 263 470 Note that now we add some overdrive AFTER THE OUTPUT of the filter \, which is quite different than having it before. This type of subtractive synthesis patch is common in 'ACID' like music. To the right we have a [moog~] object \, whose drive parameter is on the input so you can also include another overdrive to the output!, f 37;
